To dynamically import an image in React, you can leverage the `import()` function and React's `useState` hook.

Here's an example of dynamically importing the image using the `import()` function and `useState`:

```javascript
import React, { useState, useEffect } from "react";

const MyComponent = () => {
  const [imageSrc, setImageSrc] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    import("./imgs/fe8b78fa-50f5-4061-bf09-1932fc2f0beb.png")
      .then((module) => setImageSrc(module.default))
      .catch((error) => console.error("Error loading image:", error));
  }, []);

  if (!imageSrc) {
    return <p>Loading image...</p>;
  }

  return (
    <div>
      <img src={imageSrc} alt="My Image" />
    </div>
  );
};

export default MyComponent;
```

In this code, we use the `import()` function to dynamically import the image file. The `useState` hook is used to manage the state of the image source (`imageSrc`).

Inside the `useEffect` hook, we import the image file using `import("./imgs/fe8b78fa-50f5-4061-bf09-1932fc2f0beb.png")`. Then, we set the image source in the state by accessing `module.default`.

While the image is being loaded, we render a loading indicator. Once the image source is available, we render the image with the `src` attribute set to `imageSrc`.

Please ensure that the file path in the `import()` statement is correct relative to the component file location and that the image file exists in that path.

